LA  - English
PB  - American Institute of Physics
AB  - In the realm of agricultural practices, particularly in crop recommendation systems, the accurate prediction of suitable crops is paramount for maximizing yields and minimizing losses. Traditional methods of crop recommendation often prove time-consuming and financially burdensome. However, leveraging machine learning algorithms can offer a more efficient and cost-effective approach. In this study, we propose a novel strategy for crop recommendation using the Naive Bayes algorithm as its cornerstone. Naive Bayes, known for its simplicity and efficiency, serves as the backbone of our proposed approach. We conduct a comparative analysis with four other prominent algorithms: K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN), Logistic Regression, Gradient Boosting, and Rule-Based Classifier, utilizing a dataset comprising agricultural information from diverse regions. Our findings demonstrate that the Naive Bayes-based approach outperforms the alternative algorithms in terms of crop recommendation accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity. Moreover, it exhibits superior computational speed compared to the other techniques evaluated. The proposed Naive Bayes methodology presents a promising avenue for enhancing crop recommendation systems. By leveraging agricultural data, it offers a swift, reliable, and precise method for predicting suitable crops. Furthermore, this approach lays the groundwork for the development of new tools such as crop recommendation applications, aiding farmers and agricultural experts in decision-making processes. Overall, our study underscores the efficacy of the Naive Bayes technique in crop recommendation, showcasing its superiority in accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, and computational efficiency over the alternative algorithms considered. © 2026 Author(s).
