AB  - With the exponential growth of online movie resources, traditional methods face challenges in accuracy and computational efficiency when dealing with large-scale sparse data. To this end, this study proposes a hybrid recommendation algorithm that integrates collaborative filtering (CF) and matrix factorization techniques on the MovieLens platform. The method first preprocesses the data by filling missing values with neighborhood-based CF and normalizing user ratings. Then, the user-movie matrix is constructed, and the cosine similarity is calculated by combining user-based and item-based CF. Matrix factorization, especially singular value decomposition (SVD), is used to extract latent factors, and regularization is used to optimize prediction accuracy. In the above data conclusions, the hybrid algorithm outperforms the individual methods in terms of accuracy (MAE: 0.33, RMSE: 0.42) and achieves excellent recommendation coverage (0.78) and diversity (0.85). The proposed method effectively balances personalized recommendations and system performance, thus providing a robust solution. We can then focus on optimizing computational costs and integrating deep learning to improve scalability.  © 2025 IEEE.
